    ```javascript
function recoverArray(n, nums) {
    nums.sort((a, b) => a - b);
    const arr = new Array(n);
    for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        arr[i] = nums[i * 2];
    }
    return arr;
}
```

    The algorithm to solve the problem is the same for all the languages. The steps are:

1. Sort the given `nums` array in non-descending order.
2. Iterate from 0 to `n-1` (inclusive), and for each index `i`, add the number at index `(2*i)` of the sorted `nums` array to the resulting `arr`.
3. Return the resulting `arr`.

This works because the sorted `nums` array will have lower integers mixed with higher integers. Given that we have exactly n lower integers and n higher integers, picking every other number (starting at index 0) will give us the desired original array.

